# Use Result Pattern

Use the `Result<T, E>` pattern for error handling. Never throw exceptions. Handle all cases explicitly.

## The Pattern

```typescript
type Result<T, E> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: E };
```

## Why

- **Explicit** - Errors are part of the type signature
- **Composable** - Results can be chained and transformed
- **Exhaustive** - The compiler ensures all cases are handled
- **No surprises** - Errors don't propagate invisibly up the stack

